{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 13:29:16.209902", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Network troubleshooting diagnosis report\\n\\nScope and expectations\\n- Hierarchical OSPF network with hosts in 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 using DHCP and DNS at 10.200.0.2.\\n- Web services:\\n  - Four Apache front-end servers: web0.local..web3.local in 10.200.0.0/24.\\n  - Nginx load balancer web99.local in 10.200.0.0/24, load-balancing to backend servers that must not be directly reachable from hosts.\\n- Goal: detect anomalies, localize faulty device(s), and identify likely root cause(s). No remediation proposed.\\n\\nKey observations from tests\\n\\nAddressing, DHCP, DNS\\n- host_1_1_1_1: 10.1.1.10/24, GW 10.1.1.1, resolv.conf -> 10.200.0.2\\n- host_2_1_1_1: 10.2.1.10/24, GW 10.2.1.1, resolv.conf -> 10.200.0.2\\n- DHCP leases present (dynamic addresses with valid lifetimes).\\n- DNS resolution working (consistent, low name lookup times in curls to web99.local and web1–3).\\n\\nRouting/OSPF\\n- router_dist_2_1 has kernel route for 10.2.1.0/24 and OSPF-learned routes to other subnets (10.1.1.0/24, 10.200.0.0/24).\\n- OSPF neighbors: router_dist_2_1 Full with core; core_2 Full with peers; server_access_router Full with core_3. No adjacency issues observed.\\n\\nL2/interface health\\n- host_2_1_1_1 eth0: no errors/drops.\\n- switch_access_2_1_1 eth0/eth1: no errors/drops; br0 shows normal counters, no anomalies.\\n- host_1_1_1_1 and switch_access_1_1_1 show clean counters (minor RX dropped reported once on sw1 eth1, not correlated to issues).\\n- All relevant links show 10Gb/s, full-duplex, link detected.\\n\\nReachability\\n- End-to-end ping reachability generally OK across hosts and server farm with 0% loss. Example:\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 -> load_balancer avg ~2.7 ms.\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> load_balancer initially reported avg ~10.5 ms with spikes to ~19 ms; repeated tests showed 1.8–4.2 ms avg with occasional jitter, 0% loss.\\n  - host_1_1_1_1 <-> host_2_1_1_1: ~2.6 ms avg, 0% loss.\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 -> web_server_0 (10.200.0.3): 0% loss, ~2–4 ms avg.\\n- Note: Two early long-running pings from host_2 to 10.200.0.7/10.200.0.2 exceeded the tool’s 10s runtime limit; subsequent shorter pings succeeded (indicates tool timeout, not network loss).\\n\\nWeb service behavior\\n- Load balancer (web99.local, 10.200.0.7):\\n  - Accessible from both hosts; total times ~1.0–1.36 s; TTFB ~0.21–0.56 s.\\n  - LB listening on 0.0.0.0:80.\\n- Front-end web servers web1–web3 (10.200.0.4/5/6):\\n  - host_2_1_1_1 HTTP access succeeds with totals ~1.0–1.3 s; TTFB ~0.20–0.40 s.\\n- Front-end web server web0 (10.200.0.3):\\n  - From both hosts: HTTP attempts to web0.local and 10.200.0.3 consistently time out at ~5.0 s (no connect established during the 5 s curl window).\\n  - ICMP to 10.200.0.3 is fine (low RTT, 0% loss).\\n  - From server_access_router (same L3 as servers): HTTP to 10.200.0.3 does succeed but is very slow — connect ~3.0 s, TTFB ~5.2–8.1 s, total ~6.0–8.9 s.\\n  - From another server (web_server_1) to 10.200.0.3: total ~7.1 s (also very slow).\\n  - On web_server_0: iptables ACCEPT (no filtering); port 80 listening (python3); ss shows LISTEN with non-zero queues (Recv-Q 6, Send-Q 5), indicating backlog/accept pressure or slow application handling.\\n\\nSecurity/policy checks\\n- No filtering policies on server_access_router or router_dist_2_1 (iptables default ACCEPT).\\n- Design requires backend web servers behind LB to be inaccessible from hosts; no evidence of hosts reaching backend-only interfaces. The problematic server (web0) is a front-end and should be reachable.\\n\\nAssessment of network health\\n\\nHealthy components\\n- OSPF routing domain: stable adjacencies, correct routes present.\\n- Host IP/DHCP/DNS: correct and operational.\\n- L2/links: clean, no error counters, links up at expected speed.\\n- End-to-end reachability: generally good with 0% loss; the load balancer and web1–web3 front-ends function normally from the host subnets.\\n\\nDetected anomalies\\n1) Severe HTTP service degradation on web_server_0 (10.200.0.3, web0.local)\\n- Symptom: From hosts, HTTP connections time out at ~5 s; from local server segment, connections eventually complete but with multi-second connect and first-byte delays (6–9 s total).\\n- ICMP to 10.200.0.3 is unaffected. Other front-end servers (10.200.0.4/5/6) are normal.\\n- netstat/ss on the server shows port 80 listening with signs of backlog pressure.\\n\\n2) Intermittent latency jitter toward 10.200.0.0/24 from host_2_1_1_1\\n- Occasional spikes (up to ~10–15 ms) observed in some pings; no packet loss; not reproducible as a persistent fault.\\n- No corresponding L2 errors; likely transient/system noise rather than a link or routing problem.\\n\\nFault localization\\n- The HTTP issue is localized to web_server_0 (10.200.0.3). Evidence:\\n  - Problem persists even from the same L3 segment (server_access_router and peer servers), excluding host access, L2, L3, and ACL/iptables on transit nodes.\\n  - ICMP fine, other servers on same VLAN fine, pointing away from network path problems.\\n  - Listening service present on web_server_0 but slow to accept/respond.\\n\\nLikely root cause\\n- Application-layer or host-level performance problem on web_server_0 causing:\\n  - Slow TCP handshakes (multi-second connect times).\\n  - Delayed request processing (high TTFB).\\n  - Backlog saturation indications (non-zero Recv-Q/Send-Q on the listening socket).\\n- Not attributable to routing, switching, or firewall policy in the network.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- Overall network control plane (OSPF), addressing, and transport paths are healthy.\\n- The primary abnormal behavior is an application performance failure isolated to web_server_0 (10.200.0.3), manifesting as timeouts from remote hosts and multi-second delays even locally; network path is not the limiting factor.\\n- A secondary, minor observation is occasional latency jitter from host_2_1_1_1 that does not affect reachability and shows no link errors., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='c96a2c33-08fa-4058-afd5-d822ef758d89'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
